segments.text: He was in what was the old Bryan High School for the last year.
Then they built the new school.
Now that's a bunch of youngsters that had a good time.
They really had a good time.
Then he went to A&M.
He was an unqualified junior.
Isn't there some attitude there?
He had to do some extra work in the junior class.
I don't know what that is called.
But he persuaded me to let him go on in.
So that's when he tried to get in.
Then he went to Houston and got in.
But he loved airplanes from the time he could.
One of the first words he said was airplane.
And I had an old chair, one of the way back yonder kind, high back, and I put a seat in the chair that had, it looked like made of panel wood, but had designs punched in it.
And I gave, he had a box of ten penny nails and a rubber hammer that he played with.
And one day, he was in Rompers, he, uh,
put the nails in the holes of that chair, just like an airplane.
He says, Daddy, airplane.
And he was just airplane crazy all the time.
And he really did make his name in that airplane.
He catered with the brass.
Uh-huh, uh-huh.
That sounds pretty good.
What about that?
I guess, you know, over the years, I guess, in taking my history courses and stuff like that, you know, they always talked about the depression and things like that and everything.
How did it affect you?
We was in a depression.
This don't work.
We was in a depression.
We didn't know too much about those kind of things.
But we felt it very keenly.
We had to cut down on a lot of things.
And the business...
You know, you had to have gasoline, and the business didn't deteriorate too much, but it did slow down.
But he weathered the storm.
Most people did.
I don't know.
Well, let's see.
What else do I have here?
What about...
What about the community life here in Bryan College Station?
Is Bryan older than College Station?
Oh, yeah.
College Station's just grown up the last few years.
It really has?
The Boondall, you know, was the first courthouse.
That's out about two miles, isn't it?
Out east of town.
Why did they decide to move it here?
Because the railroad come in.
The railroad came in.
Uh-huh.
And the railroad had gotten as far as Milligan, and it came from Milligan then on up here.
But the railroad brought Brian over here.
And Brian was named for a Mr. Brian who had offsprings at the First National Bank here.
Mr. God brought Mr. What's the Brian boy named?
Travis.
Travis Brian.
He was his son, wasn't he?
No, he was the second generation.
He's the third generation.
And they named the town for him.
He advanced a whole lot of the financial necessities, you know.
And this Mr. Bryan's father did a lot for Bryan Air Force Base.
And he engineered a collection and got an airplane.
What's the name of that airplane, Willie Bell?
I'm getting along pretty good with a friend of mine that's come in, Miss Willie Bell Johnson.
She knows more about it than I do.
She's not near as old as I am.
What about A&M when that started?
A&M has grown.
I know that well.
My uncle was born that year.
He went to school after a little while.
And the A&M, well, a lot of the tuitions were paid from rural districts, paid with...
We had wood and everything out there then.
They took meats and cordwood and different things like that on payment for the tuitions, you know.
And a friend of mine used to bring wood over there, driving a four-mural team, you know, bringing cord after cord.
It had a contractor.
to get the word for heating system out there.
And then of course it advanced very early just from boys taking all courses and each year there would be another type of education, you know.
And so it's just really and truly
outgrown itself in a way.
And the first students were 14 years old when they started out there.
Huh?
The first students were 14 years old.
I mean, they took them at 14 years.
They took them at 14 years.
Then they went to 16.
Well, is there anything you can think of that I might not have covered that you'd like to say or whatever?
Well, uh,
Of course, we had the Carnegie Library in Bryan.
I believe it was in 1902, and it has outgrown itself.

We now have a new City of Bryan Library, but the old library, some talk about them tearing it down, but everybody seemed to want it for a museum, if nothing else, because it was a donation to the city.
But they are temporarily using it as a traffic office.
And it seems like it's working out very nicely for that, you see.
And then, of course, we've had trouble having enough water and everything, but we're still on top, I think, with everything.
And the college dances were always wonderful.
And most always, the gentlemen, the boys would take their girlfriends out in what they called, what is that old nigger man's name?
It was a surrey.
He used to take a bunch of them out.
Tally, I believe his name was.
It was a tally.
Huh?
I remember him talking about a tally.
Well, I believe it was Tally Surrey.
And he'd make trip after trip coming to Bryan.
And it was a long way around then.
See, this road has been changed two times since I've been here to Bryan.
It's the shorter way now.
But he took the young folks out.
And sometimes some of them are pretty late getting back in on you.
But they used to have wonderful, wonderful dances, which they still do.
And it's just marvelous the way that they have been able to do it.
We didn't remember distinctly when the first automobile came to Bryan.
Then for a long time, between Bryan and College Station, they had the, what do they call that trolley?
Interurban.
Interurban.
They had that there.
And I went to summer school one summer out there.
And I rode this, rode that.
And the depot was right down, right down here.
Well, right at the old fire station.
Was it over there?
Right across over there.
No, the inner urban depot.
It was at the fire station.
It was a little bit further over where the Eagle office is.
Yeah, where the Eagle office is now.
The inner urban used to have that office there.
And they run...
Trolley cars.
Every half hour, I believe.
And I got my transportation to school out there on that trolley.
And that's about all.
That's the only way.
Horse bugging horse, you know, of course.
Due to the fact the railroad ran through Bryan made the sights even more favorable.
But when the commissioners arrived and found saloons
on every corner.
The commissioners moved further out until historians say the commissioners came to a place thick with dewberries, and here they stuck a stake in the ground and said, here we'll build a college.
You ought to have that, isn't it?
Yeah.
Talking about that, was Brown a pretty wild town?
Had lots of saloons.
It had worlds of saloons, and as I said, every...
three, four doors was a saloon.
We were never, in going to town, we were never, we were always told never look in a livery stable and never look in a saloon.
But we'd cock our eye around.
We had a livery stable right on Main Street.
One big livery stable was on, Tabor's livery stable was on Main Street.
But we had ever so many saloons just, and they, you know,
It wasn't a while.
I think we are worse now than we used to be.
Really?
Mm-hmm.
We never had a lock on our doors in days gone by.
And within the last few years, why, they've had to put locks on everything they own.
I know, yeah.
And we really and truly, I remember many a night.
When we lived on North Bryan Street, one morning we waked up,
Every window in the house, every door in the house was wide open.
And on our front porch was a row of transient cotton pickers seeping on our front porch, and we didn't know it.
Golly.
I'll bet there was 10 people, 10 men out there on our front porch, and we didn't know it.
So that's how bad we were then.
But we wouldn't do it today.
What other things that you've noticed, you know, the town or the people's attitudes or things like that have changed?
Very much so.
There used to be an awful lot of man-to-man attitude, you know.
But I think now it's dollar-to-dollar.
I might be wrong.
I don't do too much trading myself.
I've been here since 67, so I don't know too much about the family.
I mean, I've been up here at the hotel.
But I have.
I've weathered the storm pretty good.
I'll be 90 years over in December, and that's a lot of years.
That's a lot of years, and you're still a little active.
